Torvalds &lt;&gt;</td></tr><tr><td class="lp">Subject</td><td class="rp" itemprop="name">Re: current linux-2.6.git: cpusets completely broken</td></tr></table></td><td><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></td></tr></table><pre itemprop="articleBody"><br /><br />On Tue, 15 Jul 2008, Dmitry Adamushko wrote:<br />&gt; <br />&gt; cpu_clear(cpu, cpu_active_map); _alone_ does not guarantee that after<br />&gt; its completion, no new tasks can appear on (be migrated to) 'cpu'.<br /><br />But I think we should make it do that.<br /><br />I do realize that we "queue" processes, but that's part of the whole <br />complexity. More importantly, the people who do that kind of asynchronous <br />queueing don't even really care - *if* they cared about the process <br />_having_ to show up on the destination core, they'd be waiting <br />synchronously and re-trying (which they do).<br /><br />So by doing the test for cpu_active_map not at queuing time, but at the <br />time when we actually try to do the migration, we can now also make that <br />cpu_active_map be totally serialized.<br /><br />(Of course, anybody who clears the bit does need to take the runqueue lock <br />of that CPU too, but cpu_down() will have to do that as it does the <br />"migrate away live tasks" anyway, so that's not a problem)<br /><br />		Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
